\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
To illustrate a test for the difference between two means, let mw be the
 mean hourly earning in the population of women recently graduated from
 college and let mm be the population mean for recently graduated men.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then the 
\begin_inset Flex Bold
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
null hypothesis
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Flex Bold
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
the two-sided alternative hypothesis
\end_layout

\end_inset

 are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
H_{0}:\mu_{m} & = & \mu_{w}\\
H_{1}:\mu_{m} & \neq & \mu_{w}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Consider the null hypothesis that mean earnings for these two populations
 differ by a certain amount, say 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}$
\end_inset

.
 The null hypothesis that men and women in these populations have the same
 mean earnings corresponds to 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{0}:d_{0}=\mu_{m}-\mu_{w}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
